{"id":"1803.10101","submitter":"Andrzej Krasi\\'nski","authors":"Andrzej Krasi\\'nski","title":"Short-lived flashes of gamma radiation in a quasi-spherical Szekeres\n  metric","comments":"18 pages, 23 figures. This paper will remain unpublished. The story\n  of my unsuccessful attempts at publication can be read here:\n  http://users.camk.edu.pl/akr/durationsmisery/durationsmisery.html","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In previous papers it was shown that gamma rays with characteristics similar\nto those of the gamma-ray bursts (GRBs) observed by astronomers may arise from\nsuitably shaped nonuniformities in the Big Bang in a quasi-spherical Szekeres\n(QSS) model. The gamma radiation arises by blueshifting the light emitted by\nhydrogen atoms at the end of the last scattering epoch along preferred\ndirections that exist in QSS models. However, the durations of the gamma\nflashes and of their afterglows implied by the model were much longer than\nthose of the observed GRBs. In this paper it is shown that for the gamma-ray\nflash a duration of correct order results if the blueshifted radiation, on its\nway to the present observer, passes through another QSS region where it is\ndeflected. The angle of deflection changes with time because of the\ncosmological drift mechanism, so the high-frequency ray will miss the observer\nafter a while. It is shown by explicit numerical calculation that a gamma-ray\nflash will no longer be visible to the present observer after 10 minutes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Mar 2018 14:23:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 12 Dec 2018 14:09:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-12-13"}
